1167	All Data	e31aff14fbb756af1a94edd631213f16	Stu_0dc1d83b0f025849c7e4985f958b923b	bdac7b030a0001dc1211d01d12c7a9a2	2021-09-06 20:55:05	America/New_York	0	ATTEMPT		RESULT		General Chemistry I	Foundations of Chemistry	Properties of Matter	conservation_submit_compare_digt	3	2021-09-06 20:55:05	q1_qsub_0 UpdateShortAnswer	1	1	CORRECT	q1_qsub_0	UpdateShortAnswer	He believed that because there aren't as many ashes compared to the amount of wood that was put in, the product is less compared to the materials. However, this is wrong because the law of conservation of matter states that there is no change in quantity of matter if matter is converted or changed into a different type of matter. Therefore we can conclude that that the wood has been converted to ash and carbon dioxide, indicating that the amount of substance after the reaction is equal to the amount of substance before the reaction.	<material><p id="a993bfe6c3fd4cecaafed35d319edf89">Although it would appear that there is less substance after the reaction (largely the ashes) than before the reaction (the wood), because the reaction does not take place in a controlled environment it is not possible to capture and measure all of the substances both before and after the reaction. However, if in a controlled environment and all substances could be collected and measured the law of conservation of matter would be observed and the mass of all of the starting materials before the reaction would equal the mass of all of the materials produced after the reaction had occurred.</p></material>				Single-KC		KC833		Santa Ana College	98907Chem209	7f60e42f0a0001dc5ec9d7e85cb58353	false	didigetthis	x-oli-inline-assessment
